{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2hayden_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280604999/1949060201/0534.xml":{"full_text":"ftp gening\nWith SunOoy Morning Edition.\nWASHINGTON. D. C\nPublished by\nThe Evening Star Newspaper Company.\nSAMUEL H. KAUFFMANN, President.\nB. M. McKELWAY, Editor.\nMAIN OFFICE: 11th St and Pennsylvania Ave\nNEW YORK OFFICE: 110 East 42d St\nCHICAGO OFFICE: 43-* North Michigan Ave.\nDelivered by Carrier\u2014Metropolitan Area.\nDally ond Sunday Doily Only Sunday Only\nMonthly 1.20* Monthly 90c 10c per copy\nWeekly 30c Weekly 20c 10c per copy\n*10e additional when 5 Sunday* ore In a month.\nAlto 10c additional tor Night Final Edition In thoeo\nsections where delivery it mode.\nRates by Moil\u2014Payable in Advance.\nAnywhere in United Stales\nCvening and Sunday Evening Sunday\n1 month 1.30 I month 90c I month 60c\n6 months\u2014 7.50 6 months 5.00 6 months 3.00\n1 year _15.00 1 year 10 00 1 year \u20146.00\nTelephone Slotting 5000\nEntered at the Post Office, Woshmgton, 0. C\u201e\nas second-class mo.I matter.\nMember ef the Associated Press.\nThe Associated Pres* Is entitled exclusively to the use\nfor republication of all the local newt printed In this\nnewspaper, as well os oil A. P. news dispatches._\nX\u2014i18 THURSPAYTjune 2, 1949\nIt Can Still Be Saved\nThe Senate Appropriations Committee\nseems unwittingly to have destroyed hope\nfor a great celebration next year com\nmemorating the 150th anniversary of\nWashington as the Nation\u2019s Capital.\nThis is all the more surprising to the\nmembers of the President\u2019s Sesquicenten\nnial Commission, who have been struggling\nagainst odds to make effective the plans\nfor the event, and to members of the\nSenate Appropriations Subcommittee who\napproved the plans and appropriations\nwith some enthusiasm. i i\nWhat happened represents one o'f the\naccidents in the legislative process. The\nPresident had requested $3,000,000 for\nunderwriting original costs of the celebra\ntion, in the expectation that most if not\nall of it would be returned.\nA subcommittee spent many hours in\nquestioning members ci the Sesquicenten\nnlal Commission. Its members are reported\nto have reached the unanimous conclusion\nthat the appropriation was merited in\nevery sense, and so reported to the full\nAppropriations Committee.\nThe full committee, with Senators pres\nent who were unfamiliar with the back\nground, cut the $3,000,000 fund in half, and\nmade that half contingent on public sub\nscription of the other half. The Senators\nevidently thought that if the Government\ncould underwrite the affair, private citizens\ncould do the same thing.\nCircumstances make this impossible.\nThe commission now is operating on a\nfinancial shoestring. It requires time and\nmoney and organization to obtain $1,500,\n000 by public subscription. But less than\nsix months remain before the Sesquicen\ntennial year. There are no available funds\nto perfect a fund-raising organization. To\nsubscribe the $1,500,000 in Washington is\nout of the question. So, if the Senate\nAppropriations' Committee\u2019s decision is\nfinal, the celebration, on the scale it has\nbeen planned, probably will be abandoned\nand perhaps should be abandoned.\nThat would be tragic. Every one, from\nthe President on down, who has studied\nthe details of the proposed celebration\nnext year has become enthusiastic over the\npossibilities of its utilization as a great\ndemonstration of American history and\npatriotism. That was true in the case of\nthe Senate subcommittee. The Star be\nlieves it would be true in the case of the\nSenate and expresses the hope that when\nthis bill reaches the Senate floor the item\nas originally recommended will be restored,\nafter its purposes have been more fully\nexplained.\nThis celebration is no mere city-boosting\nundertaking. It can be and should be\nmade an event of national significance\nand treated by the Congress with befitting\ndignity and understanding.\nThe Pact's Timetable\nIn deciding to delay action on the North\nAtlantic Treaty in order to give priority to\nthe proposed new labor bill, the Democratic\nleaders of the Senate have in effect sub\nordinated an international issue to an\nissue with a more direct bearing on do\nmestic politics. Since the President has\nnot objected, and since the Foreign Rela\ntions. Committee has yet to submit its\nreport on the pact, the decision is not\nsurprising. Yet it will come as a dis\nappointment to all who have been urging\nprompt ratification as a move to strengthen\nSecretary Acheson\u2019s hand at the current\nParis Conference.\nThere can be little doubt that if the\ntreaty had been ratified at the start of\nthe conference, the psychological effect\nwould have been wholesome. But there\nseems no good reason for an exaggerated\nview of the situation. Regrettable as it\nmay be, the fact that the Foreign Relations\nCommittee has been slow with its report\nand that the pact has been placed behind\nlabor legislation on the Senate calendar\nis not likely to make Mr. Acheson\u2019s position\nmaterially weaker at this time. At any\nrate, unless all signs are deceiving, ratifica\ntion within the next month or so seems\nflftout as certain as anything can be, and\nthe Russians probably are well aware\nof that.\nNevertheless, the priority accorded labor\nlegislation may be viewed by some of our\nfriends abroad as a disturbing sign that\nthe Senate underestimates the importance\nof the Atlantic Pact or is wavering toward\nit. To offset any such impression, the\nForeign Relations Committee, in keeping\nwith Senator Vandenberg\u2019s suggestion,\nshould submit its report without further\ndelay and every leadership effort should be\nmade thereafter for as big and resounding\na vote as possible in favor of ratification.\nCertainly, once the labor bill is out of the\nway, the treaty ought to receive the\nspeediest consideration; there will be no\nexcuse for foot-dragging or windy and\nrepetitious debate of the sort that mocks\nstatesmanship.\nThe significance of all this can hardly\nbe exaggerated. The Atlantic Pact is the\nWestern world\u2019s most important single\ndefensive instrument to achieve mutual\nprotection against the threat of direct and\nindirect Soviet aggression\u2014a shield that\nwe and like-minded peoples must wear\nuntil there is a genuine system of inter\nnational collective security. The sooner\nws ratify it, the better. Beyond that,\nwe need to back it up with limited arma\nments aid to the other signatories. House\nMajority Leader McCormack has indicated\nthat action on such aid may be put off\nuntil next year, but we ought not to put\nit off. This alliance of free nations will\nbe the more effective if we equip it with\nteeth right from the start.\nOur Economic Slowdown\nThe extraordinary and prolonged leth\nargy of the stock market is merely one of\nthe many symptoms of the slowdown that\nhas been taking place in the Nation's\neconomy for some months past. The acute\nshortages caused by the war are at an end. j\nProduction has caught up pretty much\nwith demand. The long inflationary boom\nperiod has largely spent itself, and we are\nfaced now with a deflationary situation\nwhose true significance is still being de\nbated by the experts.\nSome of those experts are pessimistic.\nThey think a depression, or at least a\nserious recession, may be in the making.\nThe lethargic stock market is not the only\nthing that disturbs them. They are\nworried by the fact that most industrial\ngroups have reported a substantial drop\nin production and that unemployment\u2014\nnow in the neighborhood of 3,000,000\u2014has\nincreased markedly since last fall, though\nsome of it has been seasonally natural.\nThey are worried, too, because bank credit\nto private borrowers has contracted\nsharply, the Federal Reserve System re\nporting that its members\u2019 loans during\nthe first quarter of this year declined more\nthan a billion dollars as compared to an\nincrease of $400,000,000 in the correspond\ning period last year.\nFurther, with a buyer\u2019s market replacing\nthe seller\u2019s market that has been dominant\nfor almost all of the past decade, tha pes\nsimists are afraid that public psychology\nmay tend to be economically unwholesome.\nThus, falling wholesale and retail prices\nhave already encouraged many prospective\ncustomers to defer their purchases in the\nhope that there will be additional declines.\nAccording to the worriers, if this attitude\nbecomes widespread, if consumers in gen\neral postpone their spending in order to\nwait for bargains, the resulting lack of\ndemand will cause production cutbacks,\nwhich will lead to more employment layoffs,\nwhich in turn\u2014together with such things\nas a listless stock market and contracted\nbank credit\u2014will give a whirl to the kind\nof vicious circle that could spin our econ\nomy into a deep depression.\nOther experts, however, take an optimis\ntic view of the situation. They feel, for\none thing, that doubts about taxes and\nnew labor legislation have played an\nimportant part in the slowdown and that\nthey will cease being psychological deter\nrents as soon as Congress lets the business\ncommunity know what to expect. Beyond\nthat, in the opinion of these more cheerful\nobservers, the basic factors in our economy\nare so encouraging that a serious reces\nsion seems unlikely in the extreme. Local,\nState and Federal government spending,\nfor example, has increased upwards of\n$7,000,000,000 over the total for 1948\u2014a\nrise that largely offsets the drop in expend\nitures by consumers and private enter\nprise. Moreover, the need for housing,\nindustrial equipment and durable goods in\ngeneral is still very great, and the income\nand purchasing power of the American\npeople\u2014who now are burdened with con\nsiderably less personal debt than in 1940\u2014\nremains enormous.\nAs for the current tendency of the buy\ning public to postpone their purchases\nwhile waiting for additional price declines,\nwhat is needed\u2014as many businessmen and\nGovernment officials like Chairman Mc\nCabe of the Federal Reserve System have\nbeen arguing\u2014is a return to prewar mer\nchandising methods. During the war and\nuntil recent months, the seller\u2019s market\nmade it unnecessary to go out looking for\ncustomers. But now, with supply begin\nning to balance demand, the consumer is\nchoosy and dynamic salesmanship is re\nquired to get him to buy things.\nIn sum, according to the optimistic\nexperts, there is nothing wrong in the\nbusiness outlook that enterprise cannot\ncure. The slowdown, as they see it,\nrepresents a salutary \u201cdisinflationary\u201d\ntransition from boom conditions to con\nditions of stability which should last for\nsome years to come because of the basic\nsoundness of our economy.\n'Bargain Basement Defense'\nThe Star hopes that everybody interested\nin higher pay for servicemen will read the\naddress made by General Omar Bradley,\nArmy Chief of Staff, before the Political\nStudy Club of Washington last Tuesday.\nIn furtherance of that end, the bulk of the\nspeech is printed on this page today.\nGeneral Bradley, with typical forthright\nness, challenges the theory that seems to\nprevail in some quarters that a first-rate\nsecurity system can be built around sec\nond-rate personnel, or, to put it another\nway, that first-rate noncoms and officers\ncan be obtained with pay scales \"that date\nto the horse-trolley age.\u201d\nAnd the Chief of Staff was not just\nindulging in a figure of speech when he\nreferred to horse-era pay. There has not\nbeen a general overhaul of military salaries,\ntop to bottom, in more than forty years.\nThe bill recently recommitted by the House\nprovided for an urgently needed readjust\nment upward in all levels above recruits.\nThe defeat of that bill was a severe blow\nto service morale. Its reconsideration and\npassage in substantially the form first\nreported is essential to a strong defense\nestablishment.\nTesting the B-36\nThe Joint Chiefs of Staff have taken a\nsound stand in opposing a public \"duel\u201d\nbetween the B-36 and jet fighters or any\npublic disclosure of results of secret tests\nalready planned. While it is important\nto test the capabilities and weaknesses of\nour bombers and interceptors, it is just\nas important to keep the findings from\nany potential enemies.\nThe Joint Chiefs have informed the\nHouse Armed Services Committee, which\nhad asked for a special showdown test, that\ntests of our strategic bombers and jet\nfighters will be conducted as a matter of\nroutine. These will include tests of the\nvulnerability of the B-36 to attacks by\nNavy Banshee jets and other interceptors.\nBut it is right that these tests should be\nfor the information of the Joint Chiefs\nin evaluating weapons and determining\nfuture strategy and tactics, not to resolve\nfor the public the much-discussed question\nof B-36 versus Banshee.\nNor would one supreme bout between the\nB-36 and the Banshee settle the question\nthat naval authorities have raised as to\nthe vulnerability of the big bomber. The\nsame is true of a single test with any type\nof interceptor. The vulnerability or in\nvulnerability of the B-36 can be judged\nintelligently only after numerous tests\nwith aD types of fighters under all sorts of\ncombat conditions. Only when such tests\nare completed and the evaluations made\ncan the soundness of the decision to con\ncentrate on the huge intercontinental\nbomber be definitely determined. For\nthat reason it is highly important that the\nJoint Chiefs should proceed in its own way\n\u2014behind a security screen\u2014to weigh the\nmerits of the B-36 and the Banshee, just\nas is done with all new weapons.\nDr. Sterling Ruffin\nA physicians\u2019 physician. Dr. Sterling\nRuffin set a standard in medicine in Wash\nington for more than half a century. His\nconnection with George Washington Uni\nversity began when he came here as a\nstudent about 1886. He was professor of\npractice for twenty-two years. Approxi\nmately twelve hundred men passed though\nhis classes. The method of teaching which\nhe developed was rigidly scientific, yet it\nalso was inspirational. A doctor, he in\nsisted, must understand the soul as well\nas the body of a patient. His influence\nwent out from the classroom and the\noperating theater to the whole community\nin terms of service repeated again and\nagain in the labors of his pupils.\nDr. Ruffin\u2019s own charges found him tire\nlessly devoted. He brought to them the\nreassurance of a calm and olacid confi\ndence. Sure in his judgments, he dealt\nwith disease simply as a problem to be\nsolved. His procedures were mathematical.\nModern theories annoyed him because, as\nhe believed, they were too adventurously\nexperimental. But he was philosophical in\nhis attitude toward even the most radical\nInnovations. Progress in medicine, accord\ning to his conception of it, must be accom\nplished by medicine itself. It cannot be\nexpected to come from outside and would\nnot be lasting if it did. What really was\nwanted, Dr. Ruffin declared, was constantly\nIncreasing knowledge of what makes people\nsick and what correctively can make them\nwell.\nNever married, Dr. Ruffin lived alone in\nhis Connecticut avenue home, surrounded\nby his books. Much of his library dealt\nwith the career of President Woodrow\nWilson, whom he attended and greatly\nadmired. When friends yesterday were\ninvited to comment on the net result of his\nlife, one of them said: \u201cHe built a monu\nment to himself in the young people who\nare alive today because he was so compe\ntent, so skilful and so downright good\nin his work.\u201d\n\u201cThe most dependable flyers have long\nnoses,\u201d says one who has studied the\nphysiognomy of many of same, and if he\nmeans the stork it would be better to say so.\nThis and That\nBy Charles E. TraceweU\n\u201cBUNKER HILL ROAD, N.E.\n\u2018\u2018Dear Sir:\n\u201cEver since Christmas I've intended to\ntell you about the little folks' custom in\nour neighborhood of decorating an evergreen\nfor the birds with strings of bread, suet,\npopcorn and raisins, each child reciting or\nsinging something appropriate to the season,\nthus making quite a ceremony of it?\n\u201cThen I also want to tell you about the\ntime when Mr. O. Possum paid a surprise\nvisit to my window sQl bird cafeteria one\nnight.\n\"The whole family watched him for an\nhour. He was sitting up eating bread with\nhis paws, just like a squirrel. We put out\nsome ham fat, left the window open, and\nhalf his body was inside the room. My\nhusband even touched him. On succeeding\nnights we put out more food, but he never\nreturned.\n\n\u201cToday I received a letter which I'd like\nto share with you and your readers. A friend\nin Massachusetts writes as follows:\n\u2018Knowing what a genuine bird lover you\nare, I\u2019m quite sure you\u2019ll be interested to\nhear this. One of the ladies here has had\nmany small bird boarders this winter who\nhave greatly appreciated the peanut butter\nand other delicacies she\u2019s lavished upon\nthem. A few days ago, starlings learned of\nher free lunches, and trouble began at once.\nShe was having a bad time with her heart,\nand simply couldn\u2019t keep getting up to go\nto the window and clap her hands, so here\u2019s\nwhat she did. She draws very beautifully,\nand she made a most vicious and vindic\ntive looking pasteboard cat. She attached\nhim to a cord. And now, from her bed. she\ncan pull one end of the cord and the cat\npromptly lurches forward, the starlings\ndisappear pronto, and the chickadees,\nnuthatches, purple finches, etc., go right on\nwith their meal and pay no attention what\never.\u2019\n\u201cI should say the movement of the puppet,\nnot the puppet itself, does the trick, but\nit makes a good story.\n\u201cSincerely, D. M. C.\u201d\n\n\u201cALEXANDRIA. Va.\n\u201cDear Sir:\n\u201cYou asked for it, and here it is!\n\u201cI refer to the copy of the Westminster\nmagazine, sent special under separate cover.\n\u201cYour reference to the dearth of spring\npoetry is challenged in these pages.\n\"Spring and poetry are inseparable in\nthe youthful heart in our Southland and\nin all sections of\\America.\n\u201cYours very truly, C. L.\u201d\n\n\u201cAnd suddenly\nMy heart sings!\u201d\nIt is good to be rescinded in such a\nthoughtful way that spring poetry is written\nby young people. We had almost forgotten\nthat!\nBut we know a young lady who is now\nat the perfect age of 17 years, who has\nsequestered herself in her rooms at college,\nand who does nothing but read or write\npoetry.\nAn expert hula dancer, too.\nYoung people love poetry and that 1s good,\nbecause middle age and old age do not\nfind poetry in life.\nIn looking over the many poems in the\nWestminster magazine, put out four times\na year at Atlanta, we found it interesting\nto see which poems appealed to us most.\nThey are. \u201cYou Are My Love.\u201d by Maysel\nLamb of Ohio; \u201cRiders.\u2019\u2019 by Rosa Zagnoni\nof Arkansas, and \u201cA Wish,\u201d by Edward A.\nAnderson of Indiana.\nJust simple statements of simple things.\nThe more elaborate poems left us cold.\nNo doubt that is the way one should feel\nin spring.\nNothing is so simple as love.\nSpring poems are bird songs, really.\nShakespeare had the right idea when he\nwrote about spring-time, the gentle ring\ntime, with a hey-ncnny-o!\nBargain Basement Defense?\nA Military- Statesman Fears That Outmoded Pay Scales\nW ill Result in Second-Rate Army\nBy General Omar .V. Bradley\nChvef of Staff, V. S 4\u2014nj\nMtfxvu |f\u00ab* 5* \u2019.s>4\u00a7,\nJKl\u00a9rt us* Pe^ ic\u00bb. &:*&y Ctmb e&\nWere this sen see pay* issue not of far\ngreater significance than Army household\nbudgets, I should hesitate to try your\npatience with this recitation of our need\nRecord Federal\nexpenditures for\narmed security\nand foreign aid\nhave already\nplagued the\nCongress into a\ndilemma where\nit must either\nIncrease taxes,\ncurtail spend\ning. or suffer a\ndeeper debt\nAt this mo\nment the Na\ntion can no\nlonger afford\nmany desirable\nprograms that\nmay benefit its\nwell-being\nRather it must\nsift its expenditures to cull out those which\ncannot conscientiously be called essential to\nour security, health, welfare and growth.\nMagic as is the term security in today s\ngits tempered world, it must not be exploited\nto cloak projects other than those of first\nimportance to the safety of the Nation.\nTherefore, when I plead the essential Justifi\ncation of a military pay revision at this\ntime. I do so with complete awareness of the\nurgency I invoke.\nFor whil? your armed forces are not starv\ning for the want of butter and eggs, the\nfailure to provide persuasive career incen\ntives is in danger of reducing us to an Army\nof second-raters. As long as qualified men\n\u2022espond in a free economy to the opportunity\nfor initiative and the prospect of reward, we\ncannot compete for promising leaders on pay\nscales that date to the horse-trolley age\nMore than any other institution, the Army\nis in the business of people. If we are for\n\u2022ver to be outbid for the services of outstand\ning men. then I submit that we shall entrust\ncur security future to \u201crejects'1 content to\nmake their way in a steady Job at steady pay.\nAn army so handicapped in peacetime can\nnot hope to produce the Marshalls and\nEisenhowers it needs in war.\nBargain personnel seldom produce a bar\ngain security system. Yet our Government\nclings to the theory that it can deal forever\nin basement prices on the talents of men.\nMaking Patriotism a Luxury.\nWe are in danger of making patriotism a\nluxury that the most able men can no longer\nafford. For today a talented young man\nmust choose between a military career and\nthe prospect of greater abundance for his\nfamily. By our failure to modernize pay\nscales, we have told him he can't have both.\nAs a result of this shortsightedness we\nhave discouraged from the military service\nboth officers and noncommissioned officers\nwith the talents to improve us.\nToday we are faced with an emergency\nthat will adjudge the competence of our\narmed forces 30 years from now. Either\nwe shall leave to our children a heritage of\ncapable military leaders, or we shall hazard\ntheir lives on the limitations of second-rate\nmen.\nInferior Inducements attract second-rate\nmen. Second-rate men Invite second-best\nsecurity. In war there is no second prize for\nthe runner-up.\nHowever successful our research in science\nfor weapons of defense, those devices can\nbe no better than the men who direct them.\nIf we expend billions on weapon research\nwhile pinching on personnel, we may find\nourselves headed toward a doomsday econo\nmy trap. For weapons in the hands of capa\nble men are weapons that win wars. But\nweapons in the hands of inept men are\nweapons that beckon disaster.\nUntil our armed forces are staffed with\nmen of such superior quality and competence\nthat they multiply in value with the passing\nof each year, we shall waste much of our\nNation\u2019s resources in fruitless peacetime\ntraining. For unless each officer and non\ncommissioned officer has capabilities greatly\nin excess of the responsibility he holds, he is\nbasically an unprofitable part of a military\nmachine.\nLeadership Standards Declining.\nAs leadership standards decline for the\nlack of sufficient Incentives for first-rate\nmen. we shall find ourselves dabbling on\nday-to-day defenses rather than investing\nIn security for the future. Reservoirs of\nmilitary leadership are more important to\nthe welfare of this Nation than pickled ships\nand lay-away planes.\nA decline in the cost of living for the\nfirst time since the war has created what\nsome observers call an unfortunate psycho\nlogical stage for the discussion of senlce pay.\nHowever, ours is no fourth round of periodic\nincreases. Instead the proposal before Con\ngress is the first overhaul of military pay\nscales in 41 years.\nBecause their wage-earners are paid from\npublic funds in the service of their Nation,\nthe families of servicemen have had neither\nshop stewards nor lobbies to represent their\nplight. As a result, we find men who after\ns lifetime of service are compensated at the\nscales of their fathers in the gas-light age.\nOur problem is not a problem of psycho\nlogical timing. Rather it is the need for\n:orrection of a long frozen injustice. Only\noy showing prospective leaders that service\npay affords them fair incentives in this age\ncan we hope to excite in them the desir\nability of serivce in the future.\nThe American people have created their\nmilitary establishment in the image of their\nown Nation. It is an institution founded\nupon equal rights and upon freedom of\nopportunity. It is an institution that has\npermitted me\u2014as the son of a country\nschoolmaster\u2014to quit my 17-cent-an-hour\nJob on the railroad, to compete for a com\nmission and eventually to succeed Oen.\nEisenhower as the Army\u2019s Chief of Staff.\nYet this is the institution habitually\nwhipped by every man with a grievance as\nthe demigod of oppression, the protector of\nprivilege and the despoiler of moral young\nmen.\nThe United States Army has permitted me\nand thousands like me to pay my way hon\norably in a career of service to the Nation.\nIt has permitted me to serve in dignity and\nself respect all my adult life a Nation for\nwhose institutions the military has taught\nme greater love and devotion. When I plead\nfor a fair reward. It is not for the generation\nof which I am a part. I do not speak as\na supplicant for a higher wage for myself.\nIncentive for Service Needed.\nInstead. I petition the Nation as a spokes\nman of the service I represent to preserve\nan equal opportunity for service among the\nyoung men of this generation. If we are\nto entreat them to devote a lifetime to the\nservice, then we must also give them the\nopportunity to serve with dignity, with\nhonor, and with prospects of an abundant\nlivelihood for themselves and their families.\nThe need for revision of military pay\nscales to recruit young leaders in the armed\nforces has already been supported vigorously\nby the President, by the Armed Services\nCommittee and by a commission from in\ndustry headed by Charles R. Hook.\nBecause the original bill introduced at\nthis session of Congress sought to repiaos\nwith equity and ju*Uc* the eeetradsetiom\nand inequities that have developed in mili\ntary pay it provided mcer.uv e increase* at\nexecutive lewis. Yet foe precisely this rea\nson the proposal was derogated by some as\na \"brass hat bill designed to cushion oS\ncers and exclude enlisted men Cnix-s of\nthe military toe often attribute to a11 offi\ncers the malfeasances of a lew. Three out\nof every five dollar* in the proposed ftrtf\nyear east for pav revision *t*e tabbed .or\nenlisted men\u2014most of them leader* m the\nnoncommissioned grade* Approximately\none half of one per cent would have gone\nto reward the brass who wear star*.\n1 once had hoped that me might lay away\nforever the cruel ficuon that officer privi\nlege has splintered the service* into casir*\nof haves and have-not* Yet we are suil\nsubjected to the perennial slander* of those\nwho seek success for themselves in civil life\nand vilify success in the service We are\nstill belabored by the suspicion that rrnk\nin the Army is a reward for villainy While\nsuccess in business is revered a* achieve\nment. success tn the Army is noisily con\ndemned as un-American and un-democratic\nIt is time we rejected the cheap emotion\nalism that pander* to the appetites of these\nin hum of the sen tees as a whipping toy.\nIt is time we acknowledged that leadership\nin the armed forces is a virtue that benefits\nthe soldier as well as the Nation he serves\nFor if we are honestly concerned for the\nwelfare of the American soldier, our hist\nconsideration should be for the quality of\nthe men who command him It u the com\npetence of this leadership and the quality\nof this command that may readily spell the\ndifference between hi* life and deeih in\nbattle.\nHigh-Grade Officer* tvwntial\nIn their constant efforts to drive a a edge\nbetween officers and men, the self-pro\nclaimed champions of the American GI are\ndoing him his greatest disservice Our only\nhope for a military establishment that will\nsafeguard the dignity, protect the right*,\nand give expression to the human needs of\nmen lies tn the recruitment of officers and\nleaders with the intelligence and compassion\nto fulfill those want* Again, I submit\nthese are the men whom we deny with 1\nbargain basement incentives\nThat tills Nation is prudently on guard\nagainst undue military influence in the con\nduct of Us affairs is comforting evidence of\nthe jealousy with which we pure free gov\nernment For while that vigilance dives\nreflect distrust in military power it also\ndistinguishes the vigor of our democracy\nand the determination of our people to gov\nern themselves according to the dictates of\ntheir conscience.\nBecause the histories of other nations are\nsmeared with tragic results of the concen\ntration of power in the hands of those with\nweapons, we have wisely surrounded our\nmilitary with a fortress of civilian controls.\nHowever, the best guarantee against this\nconcentration of force in the hands of a\nfew is to make certain that the military is\npossessed of the same fervent love for free\ndom. the same Jealous love for country, that\ndwells in the most conscientious cittxeus\nthey are sworn to protect. Our sturdiest\nguarantee against militarism must be cra\ndled in the military establishment itself.\nTo assure this, we must have armed forces\ncomposed of men with sensitivity, intellect\nand good conscience\u2014men who will nourish\nfaith in the essential nature of freedom to\npeace In the world\u2014men who will nourish\nfaith In the Importance of self-government\nto happiness In our lives.\nWhen we speak of the armed services a*\na business of people, these are the people\nwe want.\nLetters to The Star\nMan Should Dominate Lower Animals\nFor His Own Particular t'ae\nTo -h* Editor of Tbo Star\nThe position of the National Antlvivlsec\ntlon Society and similar groups which has\nbeen receiving much publicity In the last\nfew months Is a sad commentary on the\nbefuddled thinking of modern times.\nThe well-flnanced and determined oppo\nsition to legislation which would allow ani\nmals to be experimented upon by compe\ntent scientists for the purpose of allaying\nhuman misery amounts to nothing more\nthan a consideration of the animal as a\nbeing on the same level as man. Tills is\npatently absurd.\nOne of the most evident phenomena about\nus Is the hierarchical structure of the uni\nverse. One of the oldest principles of meta\nphysics Is \"As a thing acta, so It Is.\u2019* Modem\nscience has disclosed a variety of activity\nstarting with the revolution of electrons\nabout the nucleus of the atom. These di\nverse activities, each a level higher than\nIts predecessor and including those of Its\npredecessors, certainly denote various grades\nof being. Accordingly, since man is of a\ndegree of being higher than that of any ir\nrational animal and as he includes within\nhimself the full being of the lower animals\nplus his own distinctive characteristics, he\nshould dominate the lower animals for his\nown use. Otherwise there is no reason why\nthese lower animals should exist st all. They\ncertainly are not ends in themselves, as\nman is to a limited extent.\nThe antivlvisectionists miss this picture\ncompletely and are attempting On thought*\nto humanize the animals, that Is. to treat\nthem as human beings. But as long as ani\nmals cannot perform the activities of human\nbeings (particularly thought* there is no\nreason for considering them as human be\nings and too good to experiment on them\nfor the sake of human beings\nEDWARD R. O'CONNOR.\nOpposes Atlantic Fact\nBecause Some Signatories Have Colonies\nTo Utt aottsr at Tb\u00bb Bit/\nJean Dixon, in a recent letter appearing\nIn your paper, blandly states that Protestant\ngroup* are political-minded because they do\nnot believe in the North Atlantic Defense\npoet.\nBut is Mias Dixon aware that several of the\nsignatories of the pact are the holders of\ncolonial possessions, hence do not believe m\ndemocracy or that all men have the right to\nbe free? Is she also cognizant of the fact\nthat some of them are at war with these\nsame colonial peoples Consider Holland,\nflouting the opinion of the entire world, to\nsay nothing of the United Nations, and con\ntinuing its aggressive war. After all. Amer\nican taxpayers are furnishing financial aid\nto Holland for what?\nMany serious-minded people are oppoacd\nto the pact, because the end of the pact\nto war. IRENE M VAN ECKHARDT.\nRaster, the Hamster\u2019s Owner\nAdda a Few Wards te Her Rterr\nT\u00bb tfa* a*!to\u00bb at Tb* Star\nThe picture of Buster, the Hamster, was\ndelightful. Close-ups taken with my own\ncamera, a cheap little flash model, haw\nbeen a bit misty. Congratulations and\nthanks to your photographer.\nIncidentally, if hamster owners who hap\npened to read the article in The Star on\nMay 2$ try feeding their little creatures\nwith medicine dropper* to to important to\nwrap them (the droppers* in scotch tape or\nmmiiar adhesive to prevent the guick. sharp\nlittle teeth from breaking them._\nVIRGINIA LEE GRIMM.\nThe Pclittcal Mill\nTaft Act Right of Way\nForced by Labor Chiefs\n$*d*trmek%ni of \\<lant*c !'*\u00bbt\nMay Weaken in\nBr l a\nOrtar.sax! labor ha* *w\u00bb a* s:\niU aesght amend namar. i.n\nproamt Dm*rv.\u00ab adm.ituat.-a; T*\ntune :t ha* forced iS5iJS*f*\u00a3\u2019\u00bb# r-:\u2022-* w1 n i\nof the Taft-Hart,** iabo- iaa rape*\nas U>t esprr.a\u00bb of p: a.- *i\nSen* ta or* the North v.\u201e*r. **r* tv\nPari The far